{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nPass-4 coaching (move registry + deterministically rendered notes + guide_url deep-links into docs/plan-review-criteria-guide.md) currently runs only over SURVIVING ADVISORY findings. Blocking findings - the ones an agent MUST remediate before claim - get no coaching note and no guide_url. Field data: the E6/F1 oracle-strictness finding family recurred 3-5 consecutive rounds on tickets fde0/0ee8/76d2 because agents reworded ACs instead of adding the demanded executable oracle; a guide link plus a move-shaped nudge on the block itself is the cheapest one-round-remediation lever. The reviewer/writer separation must be preserved exactly as-is: moves come from the locked registry, prose is rendered deterministically, the C1 subject validator still rejects code/imperatives/solutions.\n\n## What\nCoaching over blocking findings must be widened at BOTH execution seams, plus the prompt, sidecar slim, and renderer. Grounded current shape: in src/rebar/llm/workflow/gates/plan-review.yaml the `coach_inputs` step (op `plan_review_coach_inputs`, src/rebar/llm/plan_review/workflow_ops.py:360) is bound `surviving: ${{ steps.decide.outputs.surfaced }}`; the `coach_gate` branch fires on `when: ${{ steps.decide.outputs.surfaced }}`; the `coach_notes` LLM step (prompt plan-review-coach) is bound `surviving: ${{ steps.decide.outputs.surfaced }}`; and the `coach` op (`plan_review_coach`, workflow_ops.py:475) already receives `blocking` but derives its move-trigger set from `ctx.inputs.get(\"surfaced\")` only. The changes:\n- `plan_review_coach_inputs` (workflow_ops.py:360): accept a new `blocking` input, compute `coachable = blocking + surviving` (blocking first), build instructions and triggers from `coachable`, and emit it as a new `findings` output alongside {plan, instructions}. The op's output schema src/rebar/schemas/plan_review_coach_inputs_output.schema.json is CLOSED (`additionalProperties: false`, properties {plan, instructions}) - add `\"findings\": {\"type\": \"array\", \"description\": \"Blocking + surviving findings (blocking first) fed to coach_gate and the coach prompt.\"}` to its properties (keeping additionalProperties: false - the closure is deliberate).\n- plan-review.yaml: the coach_inputs/coach_gate/coach_notes/coach block exists TWICE, structurally identical - once in the verify_branch then-arm (code-grounded/agentic path, ~lines 174-226) and once in the else-arm (non-agentic path, ~lines 252-304). Apply the SAME three edits to BOTH arms: add `blocking: ${{ steps.decide.outputs.blocking }}` to the `coach_inputs` step's `with:`; change `coach_gate`'s `when:` to `${{ steps.coach_inputs.outputs.findings }}` (fires when EITHER bucket is non-empty); change `coach_notes`'s `surviving:` binding to `${{ steps.coach_inputs.outputs.findings }}`. A unit test asserts the two arms' coach blocks remain binding-identical.\n- `plan_review_coach` (workflow_ops.py:475): derive the trigger set from the union of `blocking` + `surfaced` (it already receives both), matching coach_inputs.\n- Decision tag: `render_coach_notes` (src/rebar/llm/review_kernel/coach.py:162) gains an optional decision map (finding_ref -> \"block\"|\"advisory\") stamped onto each rendered entry; the kernel `coach()` (coach.py:195, which invokes render_coach_notes internally at :217) gains a pass-through parameter for it. Call paths: `pass4_coach` (passes.py:842) reaches it via `review_kernel.coach(surviving, registry, pick=..., ...)` - it passes the map there; the workflow op `plan_review_coach` (workflow_ops.py:475) calls `passes.render_coach_notes` directly and passes the map itself. Every coaching entry then carries `decision`. NOTE the live production path is EXCLUSIVELY the workflow ops above - `pass4_coach` in passes.py (:842) is exercised only by unit tests; it is widened identically anyway so the test path keeps production semantics, with a code comment stating that scope.\n- Sidecar slim: `build_payload` in src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py slims coaching entries to a fixed field list {move_id, move_name, subject, finding_refs, coaching} (lines ~445-453) - add `decision` to that list so the tag survives persistence (additive optional field).\n- Prompt + header: src/rebar/llm/reviewers/plan_review_coach.md reframed decision-neutral in BOTH places it anchors on advisory - the framing sentence AND the per-finding instruction at line 13 (\"For each SURVIVING advisory finding...\" becomes \"For each finding in the list below...\"), and the hardcoded listing header `## Surviving advisory findings (by id)` in src/rebar/llm/review_kernel/coach.py:123 becomes decision-neutral (\"## Surviving findings (by id)\").\n- guide_url: the passthrough attach at src/rebar/llm/plan_review/orchestrator.py:515-530 already keys off coaching entries' criteria - blocking entries get it for free once they exist; verify by test.\n- CLI: `rebar review-plan` renders the coaching line + guide link under blocking findings the same way it does for advisories (src/rebar/_cli/_llm_commands.py).\n\n## Scope\nIN: the widening above, decision tag, prompt/header rewording, sidecar slim addition, CLI rendering, unit tests. OUT: any change to move-registry contents, the subject validator, blocking/advisory decisions, thresholds, or the sidecar schema beyond the optional decision field. OUT: cross-finding conflict detection (parked epic grumpy-gland-rose).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A plan review whose verdict contains blocking findings emits a coaching entry (move_id + rendered note + guide_url) for each blocking finding. Oracle: two unit test cases - (a) 1 block + 1 advisory yields 2 coaching entries, where the block's entry carries decision=\"block\" and guide_url and the advisory's carries decision=\"advisory\" and guide_url; (b) 1 block + 0 advisories (the motivating BLOCK-only case, where today's coach_gate never fires) yields 1 coaching entry with decision=\"block\" and guide_url; `python -m pytest tests/unit -k \"coach\" -x` green.\n- [ ] The two YAML arms' coach blocks remain binding-identical after the edits. Oracle: unit test in tests/unit/workflow/ parsing src/rebar/llm/workflow/gates/plan-review.yaml and asserting the then-arm and else-arm coach_inputs/coach_gate/coach_notes/coach step bindings are equal; `python -m pytest tests/unit/workflow -k \"coach\" -x` green.\n- [ ] The workflow path produces the same widening. Oracle: unit test (tests/unit/workflow/) stubbing a StepContext for `plan_review_coach_inputs` with 1 blocking + 1 surfaced finding, asserting the `findings` output contains both and the instructions listing names both; and a `plan_review_coach` test asserting a note referencing the blocking finding renders with decision=\"block\".\n- [ ] The coach prompt and listing header no longer frame the input set as advisory-only. Oracle: `grep -niP \"advisory\\s+finding\" src/rebar/llm/reviewers/plan_review_coach.md` returns no hits, AND a unit test asserts the rendered listing header for a mixed set is decision-neutral (\"Surviving findings\").\n- [ ] Coaching entries for blocking findings survive sidecar persistence with their decision tag. Oracle: unit test over `build_payload` asserting a coaching entry with decision=\"block\" retains that field in the emitted payload.\n- [ ] Blocking-finding coaching notes pass the same C1 subject validation as advisory notes. Oracle: existing subject-validator tests extended to a blocking-finding case; suite green.\n- [ ] `rebar review-plan` output for a BLOCK verdict shows the coaching line + guide link under each blocking finding. Oracle: CLI rendering unit test asserting the rendered text contains the guide_url for a blocking finding.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` all pass."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784104954095680001,"uuid":"50ee24f6-0cfc-4754-918a-1cc573690725"}